In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to events, or subclass `Window`:

**Option 1 — Subscribe to Window events:**
```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**
```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }
}
```

**Key mappings:**
| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated` |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped` |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed` |

Additional events like `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Destroying` are also available for finer control. For platform-specific hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.
